This time, we gonna talk about one of the weirdest eating disorder called Pica. What is Pica actually?

Pica is the persistent eating of substances that have no nutritional value or to be simple the crave of something that not fit for human consumption

Ex: dirt, chalk, soap, glass etc üòñ

So how is pica diagnosed? Doctor will first evaluate the presence of other disorders--such as mental retardation, developmental disabilities or obsessive-compulsive disorder for the cause of the eating disorders. After that, doctor will run a complete medical history and medical exam to check for anemia, toxins and other substances in the blood that might harm the body. 
How is Pica is treated?
- Closed medical monitoring - Collaboration with mental health team that skilled in treating Pica
- Behavioral Therapy (training to guide what are edible and non edible through the use of positive reinforcement)

Today we're gonna talk about bulimia nervosa or otherwise known as bulimia
Bulimia disorder is an eating disorder that characterized by binge eating and purging. Binge eating is primarily done by eating large amounts of food in a short amount of period and purging is to get rid of the food that have eaten. Purging can be done by using laxatives and or vomiting. Other attempts may include the use of diuretics, excessive exercise and stimulants. 
Bulimia is frequently associated with other mental disorders such as depression, anxiety, and problems with drugs or alcohol.

There is a higher chance of suicide and self-harm on people that diagnosed with bulimia nervosa.

The most effective treatment for bulimia nervosa is cognitive behavioral treatmentAntidepressants of the selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRI) or tricyclic antidepressant class may have a modest benefit.

There are no simple answers to the causes of anorexia and other eating disorders. Anorexia is a complex condition that arises from a combination of many social, emotional, and biological factors. Although our culture‚Äôs idealization of thinness plays a powerful role, there are many other contributing factors, including your family environment, emotional difficulties, low self-esteem, and traumatic experiences you may have gone through in the past.


Major risk factors for anorexia nervosa:
-Body dissatisfaction
-Strict dieting
-Low self-esteem
-Difficulty expressing feelings
-Perfectionism
-Troubled family relationships
-History of physical or sexual abuse
-Family history of eating disorder .

Some of the physical effects of anorexia include:
-Severe mood swings or depression
-Lack of energy and weakness
-Slowed thinking or poor memory
-Dry, yellowish skin and brittle nails
-Constipation and bloating
-Tooth decay and gum damage
-Dizziness, fainting, and headaches
-Growth of fine hair all over the body and face


Anorexia treatment include medical doctors, psychologists, counselors, and dieticians. There are medical treatment, nutritional treatments, and counseling & therapy.

What is Anorexia Nervosa and Bulimia Nervosa and what is the differences of those eating disorder?

Anorexia Nervosa is eating disorder wherein sufferers fear weight gain and avoid eating as a result.

Bulimia Nervosa is also eating disorder wherein sufferers go through a cycle of binging (overeating) followed by purging, due to a fear of weight gain.

Those disorder mainly affects young women, where anorexia on early teen years and bulimia on late teen years. 
Behavioral & Psychological Symptoms of those disorders are the same; obsession with food, weight, and a "thin" body image (extreme fear of weight gain), depression & anxiety, and low self-esteem.

The different of those physical symptoms; anorexia usually extremely underweight and unhealthy figure and bulimia has a "normal" weight range for height/age but can be underweight. The similarities of both of them are physical weakness, deterioration, organ dysfunction (memory loss, absent menstruation, feeling faint, etc)

What is eating disorder? 
.

Eating disorders involves disturbance in eating behavior, such as reduction of food intake or overeating in an extreme level. It also involves feelings concern and distress abous one's body shape or weight. 
.

The most common eating disorder is Anorexia Nervosa, Bulimia Nervosa, Binge Eating Disorder, and Other Specified Feeding or Eating Disorders (OSFED). 
.
Later this week we will explain the differences between each disorders. Who knows that someone around you might be experiencing one of these disorder and need your help to get through their problems.
